svg.text: The key here is in the word “system”. The product by itself ​doesn’t relaly do much. But when a patient is able to put ​the colors, timed reminders, and the overall setup together, ​it

can be very effective. The product involves one tray of ​medicine for every day of the month. Each tray has a slot ​for morning, noon, evening, and night time medicines. The ​trays are filled up a month at a time and sit in a stacked ​stand where they are arranged by day of the month. Each ​tray is numbered on both ends. One end in red, the other in ​green. Upcoming days are in green, while days that have ​passed are flipped over once empty and shown in red. There is a spot at the front of the ​product to put the tray for that particular day. There is also a digital calendar/clock that ​has 4 daily alarms corresponding to the slots in the trays. The device alerts the user ​visually on the calendar, verbally by announcing that it is time to take the medicine, and ​also by setting of an alarm. The device even has extra loud volume levels for people with ​hearing loss. By using colors, the clock/calendar, and a repeatable process, the ​MedCenter encourages medication adherence and does so very easily with minimal ​electronic gadgetry.​3.What prerequisite skills does a person need in order to use the product/service? ​None.​4.If the product is used in conjunction with a computer, are Windows and Mac versions ​available? Include information about different options’ costs, if ​available. ​The MedCenter System is $59 plus the cost of batteries.​7.Other important information:​Reflection: Your thoughts, comments and lingering questions about this product/service:​The MedCenter is a very interesting spin on the medication adherence idea. While most ​products try to go for the high-tech and really complex systems, this product provides a ​pretty sufficient system without any of that. I think that what’s great about the product ​is the color coding. It makes following the steps really easily. The product also makes ​it very easy to get into a routine of taking medicine.
